{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564497"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:14:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:14:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16984"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16984"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.5,0.2,0.03,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9674"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68134"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9674","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9674"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16984"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4378"},{"type":"tags","id":"4512"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22801"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68134"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman attends the antenatal clinic for review of her morphology ultrasound at 20 weeks gestation. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy vitamins. She has had no vaginal bleeding or abdominal pain during the pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The uterus is palpable at the umbilicus. The ultrasound report describes a complete anterior placenta previa with the placental edge covering the internal cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat ultrasound in 2 weeks","Repeat ultrasound at 32-36 weeks gestation","Repeat ultrasound at 28-30 weeks gestation","Repeat ultrasound at 36-39 weeks gestation","Repeat ultrasound at 24-26 weeks gestation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidental finding of placenta previa on routine morphology ultrasound. She has no additional risk factors for abnormal placentation placenta accreta therefore does not need early ultrasound follow-up. Up to 90% of placenta previa cases diagnosed in the second trimester will resolve by term as the lower uterine segment grows and stretches, effectively moving the placenta away from the cervical os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound at 32-36 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This timing allows for accurate assessment of placental position for delivery planning, as placental location at this gestation is likely to persist until delivery. If complete previa is confirmed, caesarean delivery will be required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound in 2 weeks\u003C/strong\u003E is too early as the placental position is still likely to change significantly, and this information would not alter management at this stage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound at 28-30 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is earlier than necessary. The lower uterine segment is still developing at this stage, and further changes in placental position are likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound at 36-39 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E would be too late for optimal delivery planning, particularly if caesarean section is required. Most units aim to deliver women with persistent complete placenta previa between 36-37 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat ultrasound at 24-26 weeks gestation\u003C/strong\u003E is too early as significant changes in placental position can still occur after this time. This timing would not provide definitive information for delivery planning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placenta previa diagnosed at mid-pregnancy ultrasound requires follow-up imaging in the third trimester as most cases resolve spontaneously.","Timing of follow-up ultrasound for placenta previa is between 32-36 weeks gestation to allow for delivery planning.","Complete placenta previa that persists in the third trimester requires planned caesarean delivery."],"references":["Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists (RCOG). Placenta praevia and placenta accreta: diagnosis and management: Green-top guideline no. 27a [Internet]. London: RCOG; 2018 [cited 2024 Jun 23]. Available from: https://www.rcog.org.uk/guidance/browse-all-guidance/green-top-guidelines/placenta-praevia-and-placenta-accreta-diagnosis-and-management-green-top-guideline-no-27a/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16984"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T10:18:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T10:19:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9674"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68134"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/